So thinking out loud here. Are you sure we're specifying what we want here. The code is traversing TransitiveDependenciesOf and considers them protected, which is the inverse dependency order from DependingOn. So in practice given your own example:

// A
// B: Parent = A
// C: Parent = A, Protect = True
//
// -->
//
// Unprotected: B
// Protected: A, C

We're extending protection to parent of C, so A and C stick around, good.

However we're not extending protection to the children, like this:

// A
// B: Parent = A
// C: Parent = A, Protect = True
// D: Parent = C
//
// -->
//
// Unprotected: B, D
// Protected: A, C

So presumably we'd nuke C but leave D hanging with a deleted parent? is this right?

Actually yeah it seems right. Awesome.

