Whether or not to remove const fields from the OpSchema class depends on the requirements of your application. Removing const fields can make it easier to reinitialize an object using placement new, but it may also affect the semantics of the class.

If the const fields are there to enforce invariants or prevent unintended modifications to the object, removing them may compromise the correctness of your code. On the other hand, if the const fields are not critical to the behavior of the class and removing them does not affect the correctness of your code, then it may be a reasonable option.

If you need to reinitialize an object of a class that has const fields, you can consider using a copy constructor or a move constructor to create a new object and then swap it with the existing object. This approach avoids the need to reinitialize the existing object and can be more efficient than copying the entire object using placement new.

Here's an example that demonstrates how to use a copy constructor to create a new OpSchema object and swap it with the existing object:

```c++
void resetOpSchema(OpSchema& self, const OpSchema& schema) {
    // Create a temporary object using the copy constructor
    OpSchema temp(schema);

    // Swap the temporary object with the existing object
    std::swap(self, temp);
}
```

In this example, the resetOpSchema function creates a temporary OpSchema object temp using the copy constructor, which initializes all fields of the object. It then uses std::swap to exchange the contents of self and temp. The effect is to reinitialize self with the contents of temp, while leaving temp uninitialized. This approach can be more efficient than copying the entire object using placement new, especially if the class has many fields or if the const fields are expensive to copy.

