I also believe that inheriting from `AbstractFCMDevice` should be mandatory in case one wants to use a custom Device model for us to ensure that logic is preserved. But in that case we should completely refactor our models. We probably should move all the fields from abstract models to `FCMDevice` model, and in abstract models we can use class attributes corresponding to fields that are used in business logic, similar to what Django does in User model. For our case this can look like this:

```python
class AbstractFCMDevice:
    TOKEN_FIELD: str

    @property
    def token(self):
        return getattr(self, self.TOKEN_FIELD)

    def send_message(self, message, app, **kwargs):
        message.token = self.token
        ...


class FCMDevice(AbstractFCMDevice):
    registration_id = models.CharField()

    TOKEN_FIELD = "registration_id"
```

The values are always strings, `multiple_values_per_key` just determines whether or not to accumulate values in the same key or to replace them.

With `multiple_values_per_key=True`:
Key1=Value1 Key1=Value2 -> {Key1: [Value1, Value2]}

Without `multiple_values_per_key` specified (before this change):
Key1=Value1 Key1=Value2 -> {Key1: Value2}

